\description{
\code{factorial_anova()} tests whether group means differ across two or more
factors simultaneously, including their interactions. It performs a factorial
(two-way, three-way) ANOVA using Type III Sum of Squares, matching SPSS
UNIANOVA output.

Think of it as:
\itemize{
\item Testing multiple grouping variables at once
\item Detecting interaction effects (do factor combinations matter?)
\item An extension of one-way ANOVA to multiple factors
}

The test tells you:
\itemize{
\item Whether each factor has a main effect on the outcome
\item Whether factors interact (the effect of one depends on the other)
\item How much variance each factor explains (partial eta squared)
}
}
\details{
\subsection{Understanding the Results}{

\strong{Main Effects}: Does each factor independently affect the outcome?
\itemize{
\item Significant main effect = group means differ for that factor
\item Example: Education affects income regardless of gender
}

\strong{Interaction Effects}: Does the effect of one factor depend on another?
\itemize{
\item Significant interaction = the pattern differs across factor combinations
\item Example: The gender gap in income varies by education level
}

\strong{Partial Eta Squared} (Effect Size):
\itemize{
\item Less than 0.01: Negligible
\item 0.01 to 0.06: Small
\item 0.06 to 0.14: Medium
\item 0.14 or greater: Large
}
}

\subsection{Type III Sum of Squares}{

Type III SS tests each effect after adjusting for all other effects. This is
the standard in SPSS and recommended for unbalanced designs (unequal cell
sizes). It uses orthogonal contrasts (contr.sum) internally.
}

\subsection{When to Use This}{

Use factorial ANOVA when:
\itemize{
\item You have one numeric outcome variable
\item You have 2-3 categorical grouping factors
\item You want to test main effects AND interactions
\item Your data is approximately normally distributed within cells
}
}

\subsection{What Comes Next?}{

If the ANOVA is significant:
\enumerate{
\item Check which effects are significant (main effects vs. interactions)
\item Use \code{tukey_test()} for post-hoc comparisons on main effects
\item Examine cell means to interpret interaction patterns
\item Consider effect sizes for practical significance
}
}
}
\examples{
# Load required packages and data
library(dplyr)
data(survey_data)

# Two-way ANOVA: income by gender and education
survey_data \%>\%
  factorial_anova(dv = income, between = c(gender, education))

# Two-way ANOVA with weights
survey_data \%>\%
  factorial_anova(dv = life_satisfaction, between = c(gender, region),
                  weights = sampling_weight)

# Three-way ANOVA
survey_data \%>\%
  factorial_anova(dv = income, between = c(gender, region, education))

# Follow up with post-hoc tests
result <- survey_data \%>\%
  factorial_anova(dv = income, between = c(gender, education))
result \%>\% tukey_test()
result \%>\% levene_test()

}
